Because it enables them to sell their shares and get a return on their investment, a liquidity event like an IPO or acquisition may be seen as an exit for the company's shareholders and investors. Even if the original founder could still be in charge of the business, they might decide to sell part or all of their own shares at the event, which might be considered their own exit. A liquidity event may also result in major changes to the ownership and management of the firm, which can be seen as an exit strategy for the original founder. In general, a liquidity event may be seen as an exit since it gives shareholders and investors a chance to leave the business and get a return on their investment. 